  "explanation": [
    {
      "heading": "What is a Hash Table?",
      "body": "A hash table stores key-value pairs for near-instant lookup, insertion, and deletion — all **O(1) average case**.\n\nThe core idea: transform a key into an array index using a **hash function**, then store the value there.",
      "appearsAtStep": 0
    },
    {
      "heading": "Inserting Keys — Hashing",
      "body": "When you insert `\"alice\"`, the hash function computes `hash(\"alice\") % tableSize = 1`.\n\nThe key-value pair lands in **bucket 1**. Lookup works the same way — hash the key, check that bucket.",
      "appearsAtStep": 1,
      "callout": "Notice bucket 1 light up. The hash function is deterministic — same key always hashes to the same bucket."
    },
    {
      "heading": "Collision — Two Keys, One Bucket",
      "body": "`\"carol\"` also hashes to bucket 1 — the same slot as `\"alice\"`. This is a **collision**.\n\n**Chaining** resolves it by storing a linked list of entries in the bucket. Both `alice` and `carol` coexist as a chain.",
      "appearsAtStep": 3,
      "callout": "Real hash tables aim for load factor < 0.75 to keep chains short."
    },
    {
      "heading": "Lookup: HIT vs MISS",
      "body": "For a **HIT**: hash the key → go to the bucket → scan the chain until a matching key is found.\n\nFor a **MISS**: hash the key → go to the bucket → reach the end of the chain without a match. Returns `null`.",
      "appearsAtStep": 4
    },
    {
      "heading": "Rehashing — Keeping it Fast",
      "body": "When load factor (entries ÷ buckets) exceeds **0.75**, the table is **rehashed**: a new array of double the size is allocated and all existing keys are reinserted.\n\nThis keeps average chain length ≤ 1 and maintains O(1) lookup.",
      "appearsAtStep": 6,
      "callout": "Rehashing is O(n) but happens rarely — amortized cost per insertion remains O(1)."
    },
    {
      "heading": "Open Addressing — No Chains",
      "body": "In **open addressing**, there's no chaining. Instead, when a collision occurs, the algorithm **probes** for the next empty slot: `slot = (hash + i) % size` for i = 0, 1, 2…\n\nAll entries live directly in the array — better cache locality, but max load factor must stay lower.",
      "appearsAtStep": 8
    },
    {
      "heading": "Deletion with Tombstones",
      "body": "Deleting in open addressing is tricky — you can't just empty the slot, or future probes will stop early (false MISS).\n\nThe solution: mark deleted slots as **tombstones** (⌫). Probes skip tombstones but new insertions can reuse them.",
      "appearsAtStep": 9
    }
  ],

